<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><U>RSU Awards</U>. In 2019, RSUs represented 25% of the LTI award for each named executive officer other than the Chief
Executive Officer, who did not receive any RSUs. RSUs awarded as part of the named executive officers&#146; 2019 long-term incentive awards will vest in three equal annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of the grant date. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><U>Stock Options</U>. In 2019, Stock Options represented 25% of each named executive officer&#146;s LTI award. The Stock Options will vest on the third anniversary of
the grant date. In February 2019, the Compensation Committee made a change in the type of stock options awarded to named executive officers, determining to award stock options without a stock price performance condition to better align the
Company&#146;s LTI award practices with market practice and to be better balance incentive and retention value for the Company&#146;s executives. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>2019 PSU
Payouts </I></B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2020, the Compensation Committee certified the level of payouts for the Relative TSR PSUs and Internal Metric PSUs that were awarded in 2017. The
long-term incentive awards to the named executive officers other than the Chief Executive Officer were comprised of Relative TSR PSUs (25%), Internal Metric PSUs (25%) RSUs (25%) and Performance Stock Options (25%). The Relative TSR PSU payouts were
determined by Brink&#146;s total shareholder return (calculated based on the 20 day average closing stock prices prior to and at the end of the three-year performance period) as compared to companies in the S&amp;P Small Cap 600 with foreign
revenues exceeding 50%. The Compensation Committee approved a payout of Relative TSR PSUs at a level of
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
150% of target, which reflected TSR at the 89th percentile as compared to the peer companies (as a result of stock price appreciation from $41.39 per share at the beginning of the performance
period compared to $93.55 per share at the end of the performance period). Individual payouts to each of the named executive officers appear in the Realized Pay Table on page 49. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Internal Metric PSU payouts for the 2017 &#150; 2019 performance period were determined by the Company&#146;s performance against threshold, target and maximum
levels of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-GAAP</FONT> operating profit for the performance period beginning January&nbsp;1, 2017 and December&nbsp;31, 2019. In February 2019, the Compensation Committee certified Company performance against the
goals. The performance exceeded both the target performance range of $902&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;942&nbsp;million and the maximum performance level of $977&nbsp;million of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-GAAP</FONT> operating profit, which resulted
in a payout of 200% of target shares. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The cumulative <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-GAAP</FONT> operating profit performance result of $1,100 million reflects
adjustments (in accordance with the terms of the 2013 Equity Incentive Plan) for the impact of foreign exchange, acquisitions and divestitures, changes in pension accounting and exclusion of amortization expenses. These adjustments were designed to
ensure that participants are neither helped nor hurt by changes in foreign exchange rates, changes in how we measure <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-GAAP</FONT> results or the impact or timing of acquisitions or divestitures. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following tables show the Company&#146;s performance against the PSU performance goals, resulting in the payouts described above.<B> </B>
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g867884g38k94.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="14%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">*</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The threshold, target and maximum performance targets were increased during the performance period in light of the
acquisitions completed during the performance period. The methodology for making acquisition-related adjustments was approved by the Compensation and Benefits Committee at the time that the initial performance targets were approved in February 2017.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="14%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">**</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Reflects <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> adjustments, as described above. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Performance Stock Options </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2017, named executive officers were granted Performance Stock Options that vested on the third anniversary of the grant date subject to continued service and
achievement of a performance condition that required an average closing price of $65.94 for the Company&#146;s common stock during any consecutive 15 day period between the grant date and the three year anniversary of the grant date. The
Compensation Committee certified in February 2020 that the performance condition had been satisfied in June 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Tax Deductibility </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Prior to the adoption of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 on December&nbsp;22, 2017 (&#147;Tax Reform&#148;), under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code, compensation in
excess of $1,000,000 paid in any one year to a publicly-held corporation&#146;s covered employees who are employed by the corporation at <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-end</FONT> would not be deductible for federal income tax purposes unless
the compensation was considered &#147;qualified performance-based compensation&#148; (or another exemption is met). Covered employees included the Chief Executive Officer and the three other most highly-compensated executive officers as of the last
day of the taxable year other than the Chief Executive Officer or Chief Financial Officer. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As a result of Tax Reform: (i)&nbsp;the exception for qualified
performance-based compensation was eliminated effective for tax years beginning on or after January&nbsp;1, 2018, (ii) the definition of &#147;covered employees&#148; was expanded to include the Chief Financial Officer, and (iii) &#147;covered
employee status&#148; was made permanent for any executive who was a
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
&#147;covered employee&#148; for any tax year beginning after December&nbsp;31, 2016. However, performance-based compensation arrangements pursuant to written binding contracts in effect as of
November&nbsp;2, 2017 may continue to be treated as performance-based compensation and are deductible so long as the arrangements are not modified thereafter in any material respect (&#147;162(m) Transition Relief&#148;). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that PSU payouts for the 2017-2019 performance periods and Stock Option awards granted in 2017 that are subject to award agreements entered into prior to
November&nbsp;2, 2017 and not subsequently materially modified, will continue to be deductible under the 162(m) Transition Relief. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There can be no guarantee,
however, that amounts potentially subject to the Section&nbsp;162(m) Transition Relief limitations will be treated by the Internal Revenue Service as qualified performance-based compensation under Section&nbsp;162(m) Transition Relief or that such
amounts will be deductible by the Company. As described above, a number of requirements must be met under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code and the corresponding 162(m) Transition Relief in order for particular compensation to qualify for the
exception. There can be no assurance that amounts intended to constitute &#147;qualified performance-based&#148; compensation under the 162(m) Transition Relief, including, if applicable, amounts payable under the Company&#146;s LTI program, will be
fully deductible under all circumstances. In addition, the Company reserves the flexibility to award <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-deductible</FONT> compensation in circumstances where the Company believes, in its good faith business
judgment, that such an award is in its best </P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">interest in attracting or retaining capable management. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Sign on Award for Ms.&nbsp;O&#146;Brien </I></B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;O&#146;Brien was
appointed Senior Vice President and General Counsel in April 2019. In connection with her appointment, the Compensation Committee approved an RSU award of $250,000 and an Internal Metric PSUs award of $250,000. The RSUs will vest in three equal
installments on the first, second and third anniversaries of the grant date. The terms and conditions of the Internal Metric PSUs are the same as the Internal Metric PSUs that were granted to all other named executive officers in February 2019. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Equity Grant Practices </I></B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company does not strategically time LTI
awards in coordination with the release of material <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-public</FONT> information and has never had a practice of doing so. It is Company policy not to engage in backdating options. In addition, the Company has never
timed and does not plan to time the release of material <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-public</FONT> information for the purpose of affecting the value of executive compensation. The accounting for PSU, RSU and Option awards granted by the
Company is compliant with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States and is disclosed in the Company&#146;s annual and quarterly financial reports filed with the SEC. The determination of grant date fair value for RSUs, PSUs and
Options is described on pages 47 and 48. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>&#147;Double Trigger&#148; Acceleration of Vesting Following Change in Control </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee has approved terms and conditions for the executive officers&#146; PSU awards that provide for double trigger vesting of awards upon
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
a change in control&#151;which means that the vesting of these awards will accelerate only upon certain terminations of employment following a change in control. For Internal Metric PSUs awarded
in 2019, a change in control within the first twelve months of the performance period will result in conversion of the awards to time-based RSUs at target level that vest at the end of the performance period. The RSUs resulting from the conversion
of Internal Metric PSUs will be subject to a double trigger for accelerated vesting. If a change in control occurs after the first twelve months of the performance period, the Compensation Committee will assess performance against the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-established</FONT> goals (adjusted for the reduced duration of the performance period) and the Internal Metric PSUs will be converted to time based RSUs that vest at the end of the performance period for that number of
shares that would have become payable based on the goals (as adjusted) achieved through the date of the change in control. The RSUs resulting from the conversion of Internal Metric PSUs will be subject to a double trigger for accelerated vesting.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For Relative TSR PSUs awarded in 2019, a change in control during the performance period will result in conversion of the awards to time-based RSUs that vest at the
end of the performance period for that number of shares of Brink&#146;s Common stock that is equal to the number of Relative TSR PSUs that would have become payable based on the goals achieved through the date of the change in control. The RSUs
resulting from the conversion of Relative TSR PSUs will be subject to a double trigger for accelerated vesting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For RSU and Stock Option awards granted in 2019, in
the event of a change in control prior to the vesting date, the RSUs and Options will be subject to a double trigger for accelerated vesting.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_24"></A>Benefits </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>General.</I></B> The types and amounts of benefits provided to the named executive officers are established based
upon an assessment of competitive market factors and a determination of what is needed to attract and retain talent, as well as providing long-term financial security to the Company&#146;s employees and their families. The Company&#146;s primary
benefits for the named executive officers include participation in the plans and arrangements listed below.
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Deferred Compensation.</I></B> The Company maintains a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT>
deferred compensation program, the Key Employees&#146; Deferred Compensation Program, for certain of its most highly compensated U.S.&#150; based employees, including all of the named executive officers based in the U.S. Under the deferred
compensation program, named executive officers may defer a portion of their compensation, which is invested in mutual funds or converted to units that track Brink&#146;s Common Stock, according to the executive&#146;s instructions at the time of
enrollment. </P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Matching contributions by the Company are made in the form of units of Brink&#146;s Common Stock, which are subject to a
five-year vesting period from the date of original participation in the program. As a result, participation in the deferred compensation program enhances the alignment of the interests of the named executive officers with the Company&#146;s
shareholders by providing the Company&#146;s executive officers with a further opportunity to meet or make progress against their stock ownership guidelines. The Compensation Committee also believes that the deferred compensation program furthers
the Company&#146;s goal of retaining program participants, including the named executive officers, in part, because any matching contributions by the Company are subject to a five-year vesting period that begins at the time of enrollment in the
program. Because he was not based in the U.S., Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman did not participate in this program. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For more information on the Company&#146;s deferred
compensation program, see <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;Non-qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation&#148; beginning on page 56. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Pension Plans
</I></B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company maintains pension plans in certain countries in which it has operations. Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman participates in the Company&#146;s Switzerland
Pension Plan which provides benefits to Switzerland-based employees. For more information on the Company&#146;s pension plans, see &#147;Pension Benefits&#148; beginning on page 55. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Executive Salary Continuation Plan.</I></B> The U.S.&#150;based named executive officers participate along with other senior executives in the Company&#146;s
Executive Salary Continuation Plan, which, in the event a participant dies while in the employment of the Company, provides that the Company will pay a designated beneficiary a death benefit equal to three times the participant&#146;s annual salary.
This benefit is paid out over a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-year</FONT> period following the participant&#146;s death. Because he is not based in the U.S., Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman did not participate in this plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Long-Term Disability Plan.</I></B> U.S.-based named executive officers participate along with other salaried U.S. employees in a long-term disability program. In
the event that the executive is totally incapacitated, the executive would receive 50% of current annual base salary plus the average of the last three years&#146; annual incentive payments, with a maximum annual payment of $300,000. These payments
would continue (as long as the executive is totally disabled) until the executive reaches the social security normal retirement age. Because he was not based in the U.S., Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman did not participate in this plan.
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Health and Welfare Plans.</I></B> Messrs. Pertz, Domanico, Beech, Shemanski and Ms.&nbsp;O&#146;Brien are also
eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s health, dental and vision plans, and various insurance plans, including basic life insurance, and the Company&#146;s matching charitable gifts program on the same basis as any other salaried U.S.
employee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Perquisites.</I></B> For 2019, the Company provided its named executive officers with limited perquisites, including reimbursement of relocation
expenses, executive physical examinations, and payment of certain tax preparation expenses for Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman. Executives bear all tax consequences and are not grossed up. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B><I>Severance Pay Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Severance Pay
Plan provides severance benefits to eligible employees, including the named executive officers, whose employment is terminated by the Company without cause other than by reason of incapacity or terminated by the participant for good reason. A
participant would not be entitled to severance benefits under the Severance Pay Plan if the participant were otherwise eligible for more favorable severance benefits under another arrangement (including a Change in Control Agreement, see below) or
in connection with a divestiture in which the participant is offered a comparable position. The Severance Pay Plan provides the following benefits to a participant if his or her employment is terminated under the circumstances described above: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="34">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD WIDTH="1" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">a lump sum payment equal to the sum of: (a)&nbsp;the executive&#146;s annual base salary through the date of termination, (b)&nbsp;any bonus or incentive compensation approved but not paid, and (c)&nbsp;any accrued
vacation pay, in each case to the extent not already paid or credited as of the date of termination; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">a lump sum payment equal to the product of (a)&nbsp;one (one and a half (1.5) for the Chief Executive Officer), multiplied by (b)&nbsp;the sum of annual base salary and target annual incentive opportunity;

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">a prorated bonus for the year of termination, so long as the participant was employed by the company for at least six months of the performance year;
</TD></TR></TABLE></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control&#148;&#151;Severance Pay Plan beginning on page 59 for additional information about the Severance Pay Plan.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_25"></A>Change in Control
Agreements </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has change in control agreements with each of the named executive officers that are described under
&#147;Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#151;Change in Control Agreements&#148; beginning on page 62. The Compensation Committee believes that the change in control agreements serve the interests of the Company and its
shareholders by ensuring that if a change in control is ever under consideration, the named executive officers will be able to advise the Board whether the potential change in control transaction is in the best interests of shareholders, without
being unduly influenced by personal considerations, such as fear of the economic
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
consequences of losing their jobs as a result of a change in control. The change in control agreements are &#147;double trigger,&#148; which means that benefits become available to named
executive officers under the agreements only upon a change in control followed by certain terminations of employment. The Compensation Committee believes that a double trigger appropriately protects the legitimate interests of the named executive
officers in employment security without unduly burdening the Company or affecting shareholder value in connection with a change in control. The Compensation Committee reviews the potential payments under these agreements each year.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_26"></A>Compensation
Recoupment Policy </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event the Company is required to provide an accounting restatement for any of the prior three fiscal years for
which audited financial statements have been completed, due to material noncompliance with any financial reporting requirement under the federal securities laws, the Company will recoup from the executive officers and
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
any recipient of performance-based cash or equity compensation who was directly responsible for the restatement, any performance-based cash or equity-based incentive compensation that they would
not have been entitled to receive under the restated results. </P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_27"></A>Stock Ownership Guidelines and Prohibition Against Hedging and
Pledging </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company maintains stock ownership guidelines for its executive officers in the amounts below: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="34">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="19" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Chief Executive Officer&#151;must hold shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock with a value equal to five times base salary </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="34">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="19" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All other executive officers&#151;must hold shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock with a value equal to three times base salary </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock owned outright, deferred compensation stock-based units and vested and unvested RSUs on an
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">after-tax</FONT> basis (but not unexercised stock options) are all eligible to be included for purposes of satisfying the guidelines. Unearned PSUs and unvested stock options do not count towards executive
officers&#146; guidelines. Until an
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
executive officer meets his or her stock ownership guideline, the executive officer must hold at least 50% of any profit shares from stock option exercises, restricted stock unit vesting, or
payout of any PSUs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company maintains a policy that prohibits directors and executive officers from engaging in any kind of hedging transaction that could
reduce or limit the director&#146;s or officer&#146;s economic risk relative to his or her holdings, ownership or interest in Company securities. In addition, directors, executive officers and employees are prohibited from writing call or put
options relative to Brink&#146;s securities. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pursuant to an amendment of the Company&#146;s policies, effective January&nbsp;1, 2020, directors and executive
officers are prohibited from pledging Company securities. </P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TR>

<TD WIDTH="96%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:24pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><A NAME="toc867884_28"></A>COMPENSATION AND BENEFITS COMMITTEE REPORT
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis with management and, based on such review and discussions,
the Compensation Committee has recommended to the Board that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this proxy statement. </P>

Agreement between the Company and Mr. Zukerman (described on page 65), the Stock Awards and Option Awards granted to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman in 2019 were forfeited. The amounts reflected under the Stock Awards and Option Awards columns for 2019 reflect
the value of the awards granted in 2019 that were forfeited as well as the value of the outstanding awards granted before January 1, 2019 that were modified on May 8, 2019. The fair value of all modified awards was computed on May 8, 2019, in
accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718 and taking into account, among other things, the stock price on May 8, 2019 and the probable payout of modified awards. For purposes of this table, amounts paid to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman in Swiss francs (CHF) were
converted to U.S. dollars (USD) using exchange rates as set forth in footnote (6)&nbsp;below. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

Carlo simulation model. For the Internal Metric PSU and RSU awards, the grant date fair value was computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718 based on the stock price at the grant date and discounted because units do not receive or accrue

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The 2019 Stock Awards for Ms. O&#146;Brien include awards valued at $499,880 granted in connection with her appointment as
Senior Vice President and General Counsel in April 2019. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(4)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The grant date fair value for the Option awards was computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. For the 2019 Option
awards, fair value was computed based on the Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing model. For the 2018 and 2017 Performance Stock Option awards, fair value was computed based on a Monte Carlo simulation. The stock price at the date of grant was based
on the closing price per share of Brink&#146;s Common Stock on the respective grant dates, as reported on the New York Stock Exchange. The actual value a named executive officer may receive depends on market prices and, for the 2018 and 2017 Option
awards, additionally on achieving <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-established</FONT> market prices. As a result, there can be no assurance that the amounts reflected in the Option Awards column will actually be realized. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(5)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Represents: amounts paid under the Executive Incentive Plan (&#147;EIP&#148;) with respect to 2017 and 2018 performance
before any employee deferrals of EIP awards under the Company&#146;s deferred compensation program; and amounts paid under the BIP with respect to 2019. For a discussion of the deferred compensation program and amounts deferred by the named
executive officers in 2019, including earnings on amounts deferred, see &#147;Nonqualified Deferred Compensation&#148; beginning on page 56. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(6)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">For Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman, the amount represents the change during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 in the actuarial
present value of his pension payouts due to contributions during the year and changes in the assumptions used to value pension benefits. For purposes of computing the actuarial present value of the accrued benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman in the
monthly benefit, the Company assumed: (a)&nbsp;a 0.4% discount rate for the Switzerland pension plan measurement date of December&nbsp;31, 2019 and a 1.0% discount rate for the Switzerland pension plan measurement date of December&nbsp;31, 2018; and
(b)&nbsp;payments will be made on a straight-life monthly annuity basis. The following exchange rules were used to calculate the change in pension value during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2019: (i) 1 CHF = 1.10191 USD at December&nbsp;31, 2018;
and (ii) 1 CHF = 1.0333 USD at December&nbsp;31, 2019. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION TABLES </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Realized Pay Table for 2019 </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The table below provides supplemental disclosure representing
the total direct compensation realized by each named executive officer for 2019. The Realized Pay Table below includes the salary paid in 2019, annual incentive payouts for the 2019 performance period paid in 2020, the value of PSUs for the
2017-2019 performance period that vested and were paid in shares of common stock in 2020, and the value of RSUs that vested in 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Realized Pay Table differs
substantially from the Summary Compensation Table on page 47 and is not a substitute for that table. The primary difference between the Realized Pay Table and the Summary Compensation Table is that the Realized Pay Table includes the payouts of PSUs
after a three-year performance and/or vesting period while the SEC&#146;s calculation of total compensation, as shown in the Summary Compensation table, includes several items that are driven by accounting assumptions. For example, SEC rules require
that the grant date fair value of all equity awards (such as RSUs, PSUs and stock options) be reported in the Summary Compensation Table for the year in which they were granted. In some cases, the actual compensation realized by the named executive
officers may be different than what is reported in the Summary Compensation Table and compensation reported may not be realized for a number of years, if at all. Furthermore, realized compensation for a named executive officer for any given year may
be greater or less than the compensation reported in the Summary Compensation Table for that year depending on fluctuations in stock prices on the grant and vesting dates, differences in equity grant values from year to year and SEC reporting
requirements. Realized pay amounts for Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman are not included in the following table as he ceased to be an executive officer in June 2019. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

vested in 2019, and includes an off-cycle grant in 2018 to Mr. Shemanski, which vested in 2019. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_30"></A>Grants of Plan-Based Awards </B></P>

the Compensation Committee will determine the PSU payout based on the Company&#146;s Relative TSR compared to S&amp;P MidCap 400 companies with foreign revenues that exceed 50% of total revenues, multiplied by the number of target units. The number

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION TABLES </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(5)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">In accordance with the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan, the exercise price for the Options reported in this column was based
on the closing price of Brink&#146;s Common Stock on the respective grant dates, as reported on the New York Stock Exchange. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(6)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Grant date fair value for all equity awards was computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. For the Relative TSR
PSUs, the grant date fair value was computed based on a Monte Carlo simulation model. Under that model, the TSR PSU awards had a per share grant date fair value of $105.57 (for the February 21, 2019 grant date) and $99.38 (for the April 25, 2019
grant date). For Options, fair value was computed based on the Black-Scholes-Merton model. Under that model, the Option awards had a per share grant date fair value of $21.60 (for the February 21, 2019 grant date) and $21.24 (for the April 25, 2019
grant date). For Internal Metric PSU awards and RSU awards, the grant date fair value was based on the closing stock price at the grant date, adjusted for a discount for dividends not received or accrued during the vesting period. Accordingly, for
the 2019 Internal Metric PSU awards, which vest at the end of a three-year service period, the grant date per share fair value was $77.53 (for the February 21, 2019 grant date) and $76.69 (for the April 25, 2019 grant date). For the RSU awards,
which vest ratably over a three-year service period, the weighted average per share grant date fair value was $78.10 (for the February 21, 2019 grant date) and $77.26 (for the April 25, 2019 grant date). </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(7)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Ms. O&#146;Brien was granted certain awards in connection with her appointment as Senior Vice President and General
Counsel in April 2019. Included in the IM PSU grant are 3,259 target units with a grant date fair value of $249,933 and included in the RSU grant are 3,235 units with a grant date fair value of $249,947. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Mr. Zukerman was no longer serving as an executive officer as of June 28, 2019. Pursuant to the terms of the Consulting
Agreement between the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman (described on page&nbsp;65), the awards reflected under the Equity Incentive Plan Awards, Stock Awards and Option Awards columns granted to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman on February&nbsp;21, 2019 were
forfeited.</P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(9)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The amounts reflected under the Equity Incentive Plan Awards, Stock Awards and Option Awards columns dated May&nbsp;8,
2019 reflect the value of the outstanding awards granted before January&nbsp;1, 2019 that were modified on May&nbsp;8, 2019 pursuant to the Consulting Agreement and are not new equity award grants to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman. The vesting terms of
Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman&#146;s pre-2019 outstanding equity awards were modified under the Consulting Agreement to allow for continued vesting of these awards through March 2021, the expiration of the consulting period under the Consulting Agreement
described on page&nbsp;65. The fair value of all modified awards was computed on May&nbsp;8, 2019, in accordance with FASB ASC Topic&nbsp;718<B>. </B>The <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-2019</FONT> outstanding equity awards are shown in this
table at the original award or remaining award quantities with the fair values as of the award modification date. There were no changes to the exercise prices related to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman&#146;s Options. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(10)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">These awards modified on May 8, 2019 were originally granted to Mr. Zukerman on July 28, 2016. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(11)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">These awards modified on May 8, 2019 were originally granted to Mr. Zukerman on February 17, 2017.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(12)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">These awards modified on May 8, 2019 were originally granted to Mr. Zukerman on February 22, 2018.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Equity Award Grants </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The 2017 Equity Incentive Plan, which was approved by the Company&#146;s shareholders in May 2017, is designed to provide
an additional incentive for the officers and employees who are key to the Company&#146;s success. The Compensation Committee administers the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan, is authorized to select key employees of the Company and its subsidiaries to
participate in the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan and has the sole discretion to grant eligible participants equity awards, including stock options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock, performance stock, restricted stock units, performance
stock units, other stock-based awards, cash awards, or any combination thereof. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The exercise price of any stock option, the grant price of any stock appreciation
right, and the purchase price of any security that may be purchased under any other stock-based award may not be less than 100% of the fair market value of the stock or other security on the date of the grant of the option, right or award. Under the
2017 Equity Incentive Plan, determinations of the fair market value of shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock are based on the closing price on the grant date and determinations of fair market value with respect to other instruments are made in
accordance with methods or procedures established by the Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Equity awards granted under the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan have specific terms and
conditions approved by the Compensation Committee. In general, awards are canceled following termination of
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
employment (although vested stock options may be exercised within 90 days following termination). Upon termination of employment by reason of the holder&#146;s retirement or permanent and total
disability, awards remain outstanding and continue to vest (or remain exercisable in the case of vested stock options) in accordance with their terms. In the event of the holder&#146;s death while employed: (i) the holder&#146;s beneficiary will be
entitled to receive a pro-rata portion of the number of shares that would have been payable under performance awards notwithstanding the holder&#146;s death, based on the number of days in the performance period that elapsed prior to termination;
(ii) restrictions on restricted stock units lapse as of the date of the holder&#146;s death (or if later, the one year anniversary of the restricted stock unit grant); and (iii) outstanding options become fully exercisable as of the holder&#146;s
death (or, if later, the one year anniversary of the stock option grant) and may be exercised by the holder&#146;s beneficiary within three years following the holder&#146;s death (but not after the expiration date of the stock option award). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For a description of the treatment of equity awards upon change in control, see page 42. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For a discussion of the principles applied in administering the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan, see &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#151;2019 Compensation
Decisions by Component&#151;Long-Term Incentive Compensation&#151;Equity Awards under the 2017 Equity Incentive Plan&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;39.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Other</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Have</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Not</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Vested</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>(#)</B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00pt solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00pt solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="padding-bottom:3pt ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00pt solid #0033a0">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Equity</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Incentive</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Plan</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Awards:</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Market&nbsp;or</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Payout</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Value of</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Unearned</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Shares,</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Units,</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>or Other</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Rights</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>That</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Have Not</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>Vested<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(3)(4)(5)</SUP></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>($)</B></FONT></P></TD>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">In accordance with the Company&#146;s 2013 Equity Incentive Plan and 2017 Equity Incentive Plan, the exercise prices for
the options were based on the closing prices of Brink&#146;s Common Stock on the date of grant as reported on the New York Stock Exchange. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(2)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">RSUs vest as to one third of the total number of shares covered by such award on each of the first, second and third
anniversaries of the date of grant. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(3)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Market value or payout value was based on the closing price of Brink&#146;s Common Stock on December&nbsp;31, 2019, as
reported on the New York Stock Exchange. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(4)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Represents market value or payout value for IM PSU and Relative TSR PSU awards granted in 2017 for the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2017-2019</FONT> performance period, granted in 2018 for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2018-2020</FONT> performance period and granted in 2019 for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2019-2021</FONT> performance
period. These awards become earned and payable on the date in the first half of the third year following the grant date on which the Compensation Committee determines that achievement of the performance goals for the applicable performance period.
The number of shares of stock shown as not yet vested are based on the threshold level of performance for each of underlying awards&#146; metrics or, if performance to date on the metric has exceeded the threshold level, the level of performance
achieved at December&nbsp;31, 2019. Accordingly, for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2017-2019</FONT> performance period, the IM PSU awards are reported at the maximum 200% level of performance and the Relative TSR PSU awards are reported at
the maximum 150% level of performance. For the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2018-2020</FONT> performance period, the IM PSU awards are reported at a target 100% level of performance and the Relative TSR PSU awards are reported at a 116% level of
performance. For the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2019-2021</FONT> performance period, the IM PSU awards are reported at the threshold 50% level of performance and the Relative TSR PSU awards are reported at a 141% level of performance.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Pursuant to the terms of the Consulting Agreement between the Company and Mr. Zukerman (described on page 65), the
long-term incentive awards granted to Mr. Zukerman in 2019 were forfeited. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Outstanding Equity Awards Table Narrative </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B><I>Performance Share Units </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For lnternal Metric PSUs awarded in 2017 and 2018, a change in control within the first twelve months of the performance period will result in a conversion of the awards
to time-based RSUs at target level that vest on the vesting date (as set forth in the award agreement). lf a change in control occurs after the first twelve months of, but prior to the end of the performance period, the award will convert into
time-based RSUs that vest on the vesting date for that number of shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock that would have become payable based on the goals achieved (adjusted for the shortened performance period) through the date of the change in
control. lf a change in control occurs after the end of the performance period but prior to the vesting date, the award will become payable on the vesting date. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For
Relative TSR PSUs awarded in 2017 and 2018, a change in control during the performance period will result in a conversion of the awards to time-based RSUs that vest on the vesting date for that number of shares that would have become payable based
on the goals achieved through the date of the change in control. lf a change in control occurs after the end of the performance period but prior to the vesting date, the award will become payable on the vesting date. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For RSUs, in the
event of a change in control prior to the vesting date, the RSUs will be subject to a double trigger for accelerated vesting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B><I>Stock
Options </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Performance Stock Options granted in 2018 to all
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
executive officers other than Mr.&nbsp;Pertz: (1)&nbsp;vest and become exercisable on the third anniversary of the grant date only if the average closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock
during any 15 day period between the grant date and the three year anniversary of the grant date is 125% of the closing price on the grant date; and (2)&nbsp;expire six years after the date of grant. Two types of Performance Stock Options were
awarded to Mr.&nbsp;Pertz in 2018. Half of the Performance Stock Options awarded vest and become exercisable on the third anniversary of the grant date only if the average closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock during any 15 day period
between the grant date and the three year anniversary of the grant date is 125% of the closing price on the grant date. The other half of Performance Stock Options awarded to Mr.&nbsp;Pertz in 2018 vest and become exercisable on the third
anniversary of the grant date only if the average closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock during any 15 day period between the grant date and the three year anniversary of the grant date is 150% of the closing price on the grant date. All
of the Performance Stock Options awarded to Mr.&nbsp;Pertz in 2018 expire six years after the date of grant. With respect to all of the Performance Stock Options, upon a change in control, the price targets applicable to the Performance Stock
Options awards cease to apply. In addition, if the awards do not remain outstanding or the successor company does not assume the award or provide a substitute, then the price targets shall be deemed achieved and the awards shall vest in full upon
change in control. In the event of termination following change in control (other than termination by the company for cause or by the employee without good reason), then the award will vest in full without regard to the price targets.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_33"></A>Pension Benefits </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company provides retirement benefits to certain employees around the world. Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman participates in the
Brink&#146;s Switzerland Pension Plan (The &#147;Swiss Pension Plan&#148;), which is discussed below. Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman is the only named executive officer who is covered by this plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table presents information as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 concerning each defined benefit
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
plan of the Company that provides for payments to be made to the named executive officers at, following or in connection with retirement. Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman is the only named executive officer
listed in the table below because he is the only named executive officer who participates in any pension plan. </P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">This column shows the present value of the accumulated benefit as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For purposes of computing the present value of the accrued benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman, the Company used the
following assumptions: (a)&nbsp;the retirement age is the earliest one (age 65 for males) permitted under the pension plan; (b)&nbsp;a 0.4% discount rate for the pension plan measurement date of December&nbsp;31, 2019; and (c)&nbsp;payments will be
made on a straight-life monthly annuity basis. These assumptions are the same as are used to value the Company&#146;s pension obligations in the financial statements as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. In addition, the Company has assumed
Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman will attain the age of 65; longevity is determined using the LPP/BVG2015-Generational mortality table for payment calculations.
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B><I>Brink&#146;s Switzerland Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company maintains the Swiss Pension Plan, which is a contribution-based plan that covers all Switzerland employees, with a guarantee of a minimum interest credit and
fixed conversion rates at retirement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The amount financed for the benefit payable to an employee is based on a percentage of the insured salary and depends on the
age attained of the member; 10% from age 25, 13% from age 35, 16% from age 45 and 20% from age 55. The financing is split between the employee (40% of total cost) and the employer (60% of total cost). The risk benefits are expressed as a percentage
of the participant&#146;s salary, which annual cost is also split between the employee (40% of total cost) and the employer (60% of total cost).
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#0033a0"><B>The Brink&#146;s Company </B></FONT></P>
<p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Subject to certain limitations, an employee who retires before he or she reaches age 65, provided he or she has reached
the age of 58, may receive an annuity for life payable on a monthly basis beginning on his or her early retirement date at an annual rate not to exceed the maximum possible <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">old-age</FONT> savings
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
tables which are based on a percentage of the participant&#146;s salary. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The plan provides for payment options
of an annuity for life or as a lump sum payment. Benefit elections must be made before retirement and are subject to certain requirements, such as spousal consent.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="toc867884_34"></A><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #0033a0">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; width:48%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table presents information about the Company&#146;s deferred compensation program, which provides for the
deferral of compensation paid to or earned by the named executive officers on a basis that is not tax qualified (i.e., the Company is not entitled to take a tax deduction for the related expense until payments are actually made to the participants).
Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman did not participate in the deferred compensation program because he did not reside in the United States.
</P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-left:3%; width:49%;padding-right:0%;padding-bottom:8pt;overflow:hidden;padding-top:3pt">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The information included in the table below reflects elective deferrals, Company matching contributions, dividends
credited to the participants&#146; accounts during 2019, aggregate withdrawals and the aggregate balance of deferred compensation accounts at December&nbsp;31, 2019. Because deferrals, along with any matching contributions, related to annual
incentive payouts under the BIP or the EIP are credited in the year after they are earned, these amounts differ from the annual incentive payments in the Summary Compensation Table, which, for each year, reflect amounts earned in that year.
</P></div><div style="clear:both; height:0pt; font-size:0pt">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Under the deferred compensation program, a participant is permitted to defer base salary, annual incentive amounts earned
under the EIP (prior to 2019) or BIP and amounts in excess of 401(k) limits (as supplemental savings). The dollar value of deferred amounts is converted into notional investments in mutual funds, selected by the participant, or common stock units
that represent an equivalent number of shares of Brink&#146;s Common Stock in accordance with the formulas in the deferred compensation program. The following table sets forth the amount of salary and annual incentive awards deferred in 2019 under
the deferred compensation program by each of the named executive officers with the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Zukerman, who did not participate in the deferred compensation program: </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
